Economists talking stocks. Stock jocks talking economy. Traders talking politics. Strategists talking trading. Technicans talking fundamentals. Fundamentalists talking technical. The world is upside down. Everyone has an answer to every question regardless of

his/her body of knowledge. @SquawkCNBC @tomkeene When was the last time someone of fin tv said, "I don't know." thestreet.com/story/12451367… Not since Jeff Specoli in Fast Times at Ridgemont High. piped.video/watch?v=bc2muGlQ… @Sarge986 @riskreversal I don't know the answer.
@guyadami @terranovajoe

Read the headlines if you wish, believe the short term moves influenced by machines and algos (who know everything about price and nothing about value) if you dare - but I would reduce your portfolio's VAR (value at risk) on rallies and keep larger than normal cash reserves.

"TINA" (there is no alternative) is a bull market term . "CITA" (cash is the alternative) is a term used after a valuation based S&P advance in 2019 and after a decade long economic and market recovery - as the manufacturing recession seeps into the services space. I might be

wrong - but I am data based and not looking at the rear view mirror. Enjoy the weekend. @SullyCNBC @carlquintanilla @riskreversal @guyadami @terranovajoe I ended yesterday in market neutral exposure - planning to sell any further rally. Seems as right s the NY Yankees
but it is just my opinion based on the data and valuation backdrop. Enjoy the weekend.

@tomkeene @business @SquawkCNBC @cnbcfastmoney @andrewrsorkin @beckyquick @Sarge986 Warren Buffett famously said that investment vision/wisdom is always 20/20 when viewed in the rear view mirror. The talking heads and "first level thinkers" have confidently said that the

consumer/services remains buoyant - ignoring the June payroll report which represented the third straight month of downward revisions. The last two months have had two additional downward revisions. And then yesterday's dour data hit. A guest on @cnbc says ignore this and

look at the markets' favorable response/turn yesterday. Many of the same heads said something similar 2 1/2 weeks ago when the S&P reversed a -27 handle drop to even (and back up over 3000). Some said confidently that this indicated a new bull market leg. Opps (we havent heard

from them yet!). We rarely do when mistakes are made. Even big mistakes. To me, yesterday's rally was an oversold bounce full of sound and fury signifying nothing. All the high frequency data suggest the manufacturing recession is seeping into the consumer and services space.
